{{Orphan|date=November 2015}}

'''Hakuraku''' (伯楽, aka '''Sun Yang''' (孫陽) or '''Po Lo''') was a hero in Oriental mythology. Dispatched by the Chinese Emperor with the task of locating the perfect horse, Hakuraku returned with news of a bay mare that he had found. However, when Imperial soldiers were sent to fetch the horse, they found it was a black stallion instead.<ref name="The Awakening of Japan">{{cite book|title=The Awakening of Japan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b9x_qvmN1skC&pg=PA79|accessdate=9 July 2012|publisher=Forgotten Books|isbn=978-1-4400-3231-8|pages=79–82}}</ref><ref name="Legend in Japanese Art">{{cite book|title=Legend in Japanese Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EeRJEq3syo0C&pg=PR213|accessdate=9 July 2012|publisher=Forgotten Books|isbn=978-1-4400-8392-1|pages=213–214}}</ref>

The story illustrates the Confucian and Taoist adage that expert knowledge embodies the ability to see past exterior appearances to the true nature of a subject.<ref name="Volker1950">{{cite book|author=T. Volker|title=The Animal in Far Eastern Art and Especially in the Art of the Japanese Netsuke, with References to Chinese Origins, Traditions, Legends, and Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XyEVAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA101|accessdate=9 July 2012|year=1950|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-04295-7|pages=101}}</ref><ref name="The Chrysanthemum">{{cite book|title=The Chrysanthemum|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3VIAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=9 July 2012|year=1881|publisher=R. Meiklejohn & Company|page=41}}</ref>

The term ''hakuraku'' is now used as Japanese slang for a veterinarian.<ref name="Legend in Japanese Art"/><ref name="Association1919">{{cite book|author=Ohio State University. College of Veterinary Medicine. Alumni Association|title=Veterinary alumni quarterly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I3wgAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=9 July 2012|year=1919|page=104}}</ref>

