{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}
[[File:Green Gulch Farm Dinner Gong.jpg|thumb|right|250px|An umpan at [[Green Gulch Farm Zen Center]]]]
An '''''umpan''''' ({{nihongo|'''umpan'''|雲版}}, {{zh|c=雲版|p=yún bǎn}}, literally "cloud plate")  is a flat [[gong]], usually [[bronze]], which is rung at mealtime in a [[Zen]] [[monastery]]. Literally translated as "cloud plate," the umpan is also sounded to "signal other events,"<ref name="baroni">Baroni, 364</ref> such as a call to the conclusion of [[zazen]].<ref>Sogen, xii</ref> Typically one will find an umpan outside the kitchen (J. [[Kuri (kitchen)|kuri]]) or dining hall area. According to [[Helen J. Baroni]], "Wooden boards (''han'') hanging on various buildings throughout the temple grounds are sounded simultaneously to alert the members of the community beyond the range of the umpan."<ref name="baroni"/>

